<DOC><DOCNO> AP890201-0210 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1937EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-NorthernIreland 1stLd-Writethru   02-01 0412</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0736,0422</SECOND><HEAD>IRA Bomb Kills Soldier</HEAD><HEAD>EDS: ADDS 6 grafs to UPDATE with two more bombs. No pickup.</HEAD><DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An IRA bomb hidden in adrainpipe outside a pub exploded, killing a British soldier andwounding another as the two walked by on patrol, police saidWednesday.   The outlawed Irish Republican Army, which is fighting Britishrule in the province, claimed in a coded message to newsorganizations that it was responsible for the Tuesday night attack.   The bomb exploded as a joint army-police foot patrol passed thepub Tuesday night in the Falls Road area, a Roman Catholic enclaveand IRA stronghold in west Belfast.   Police said infantryman Pvt. Nicholas David Peacock, 20, who wason his second day of duty in Northern Ireland when the attackoccurred, died early Wednesday while undergoing surgery for woundsto his legs and lower body.   The other soldier suffered slight injuries, officials said.   Peacock's father, David, who lives in Prime Minister MargaretThatcher's hometown of Grantham in Lincolnshire, said: ``It isbarbaric that a lad out on peaceful patrol should be blown up likethat. But it won't alter my position one bit. I still believe thearmy should stay put. It has my full backing.''   A police spokesman said on condition of anonymity that the bombwas concealed in a drainpipe on the wall of the pub and containedabout 2 pounds of explosives ``with a command wire running to anentry at the rear'' of the pub.   The predominantly Catholic IRA is fighting to oust the Britishand unite the Protestant-dominated province with the Catholic IrishRepublic under a leftist administration.   Later, a bomb attached to a lamppost exploded, injuring onepoliceman slightly, as police evacuated an area in Belfast citycenter, a police spokesman said.   Police began clearing an area of Oxford Street after a bomb wasthrown over the wall of a police station Wednesday evening. The bombfailed to explode but as police evacuated the area, a second bombwent off, the spokesman said.   He said the injured policeman was treated at a local hospital andreleased.   No one claimed responsibility, but two men were being questionedabout the bombing, the spokesman said.   Also Wednesday evening, a bomb was thrown at a joint police andarmy patrol in Londonderry city center, the spokesman said.   Police fired at the bombers but were ``not claiming any hits,''he said. No one was injured.</TEXT></DOC>